statement.p:
Consider the following DeMorgan Law:

\[
\overline{(A \cap B)} = \overline{A} \cup \overline{B}.
\]






 Prove this law using a Venn diagram








Both of your Venn diagrams will look  like this:




\begin{tikzpicture}

\draw[thick, fill=blue!50, opacity=.5] (0,4) rectangle (5.5,0);


\begin{scope}
\clip (2,2) circle (1.5);
\clip (3.5,2) circle (1.5);

\fill[white] (0,4) rectangle (5.5,0);

\end{scope}

\draw[very thick] (2,2) circle (1.5);
\draw[very thick] (3.5,2) circle (1.5);

\node at (1.5,2) {A};
\node at (4,2) {B};



\end{tikzpicture}














 Prove this law using a carefully argued double inclusion proof.




First, we prove that if x \in \overline{(A \cap B)} then x \in \overline{A} \cup \overline{B}.


\begin{array}{rcl}
x \in \overline{(A \cap B)}
& \Rightarrow & \mbox{ NOT } ( x \in A \cap B) \\
& \Rightarrow & \mbox{ NOT } ( x \in A \mbox{ AND } x \in  B) \\
& \Rightarrow & \mbox{ NOT } (  x \in A) \mbox{ OR } \mbox{NOT } ( x \in  B) \\
& \Rightarrow &   x \in \overline{A} \mbox{ OR }  x \in  \overline{B} \\
& \Rightarrow &   x \in \overline{A}  \cup  \overline{B} \\
\end{array}


Let's talk about that third step, since this is a new idea. We know that the statement "x  \in A AND x \in B" is FALSE. So (at least) one of these statements is FALSE. In other words, either x \notin A or x \notin B.




Next, we prove that if x \in \overline{A} \cup \overline{B} then x \in \overline{(A \cap B)}. If you look carefully, this is just the previous argument in reverse. (This happens for simpler problems.)

\begin{array}{rcl}
x \in \overline{A}  \cup  \overline{B}  & \Rightarrow &   x \in \overline{A} \mbox{ OR }  x \in  \overline{B} \\
& \Rightarrow & \mbox{ NOT } (  x \in A) \mbox{ OR } \mbox{NOT } ( x \in  B) \\
& \Rightarrow & \mbox{ NOT } ( x \in A \mbox{ AND } x \in  B) \\
& \Rightarrow & \mbox{ NOT } ( x \in A \cap B) \\
& \Rightarrow &  x \in \overline{(A \cap B)}  \\
\end{array}

Let's talk about the third step in this case. We know that either x \notin A or x \notin B. Therefore is is NOT true that "x \in A and x \in B are both true".
